## How to Read a Regulatory Consultation

Key mindset principles for assessing and responding to proposed regulatory changes.

| Principle | What it means in practice |
|---|---|
| **Safety vs complexity tradeoff** | Ask whether each new requirement genuinely reduces risk, or adds process burden without a clear safety benefit. |
| **Prescriptive vs outcome-based** | Prescriptive rules (specific distances, exact documents) can become barriers to adaptation. Outcome-based rules give operators flexibility to manage risk appropriately. |
| **Scalability of pathways** | Will this work for one operator doing one job, or a large ReOC managing dozens of jobs? Good regulation should support both without different burdens for the same risk. |
| **Consistency across risk profiles** | Similar operational risks should face similar regulatory treatment. Inconsistency between pathways or aircraft categories undermines trust and creates arbitrage. |
| **Transition fairness** | Operators who invested under existing frameworks deserve pragmatic transition arrangements. Regulatory change should not punish compliance with prior rules. |
| **Administrative burden test** | Every new notification, document, or approval step has a cost. Ask: does this step produce an action from CASA, or is it process for the sake of process? |

