## AAUS Industry Themes – Summary

Recurring ideas raised across the AAUS submission, reflecting broader industry thinking on how to assess and give feedback on regulatory proposals.

| Theme | Core concern | Relevant section(s) |
|---|---|---|
| **Framework complexity** | Multiple pathways, categories, conditions and approval triggers risk becoming difficult to apply consistently and increasing operator confusion. | General, 5.5, 5.6, 5.8 |
| **Avoid prescriptive inputs** | Overly narrow CONOPS or fixed procedural requirements can become a hazard by discouraging sensible adaptation in dynamic field conditions. | 5.1, 5.5, 5.7 |
| **Process without safety benefit** | 7-day advance notification (5.3) and mandatory joint-assessment of combined approvals (5.2) were questioned where CASA does not intend to act on the information. | 5.2, 5.3 |
| **PRS as mitigator, not pathway** | A parachute recovery system should be treated as one risk control within an integrated safety case, not as a standalone regulatory category. | 5.8 |
| **Consistency across risk profiles** | Similar operational risks should face similar regulatory treatment. Inconsistency in kinetic energy thresholds, categories and mitigations undermines the framework. | 5.6, General |
| **Recognise operator maturity** | Organisational capability, SMS, and operational maturity should function as risk mitigators — not just prescriptive certification credentials. | General, 5.1, 5.5 |
| **ReOC / micro-RPA alignment** | Sub-250g operations should be facilitated under a ReOC framework, not only under individual RePL, to align with proportionate risk-based oversight. | 3.2 |
| **Clarify who can access each pathway** | The barrier exemption (Section 4.2) does not clearly state whether it applies to ReOC holders, Excluded Category operators, or recreational users. | 4.2 |
| **SORA alignment** | AAUS encouraged greater alignment with SORA-style operational risk methodology as a more internationally consistent and genuinely risk-based approach. | 5.6, General |

